<PageLayout
  title="How to Debug an LLM Request Payload"
  description="Debug an OpenAI or Claude request payload step by step: verify message order, system instructions, tool arguments, escaping and the exact data sent by your app."
  h1="How to Debug an LLM Request Payload"
  path="/guides/debug-llm-request-payload"
  article
  published="2026-07-20"
  updated="2026-07-20"
>
  <p>
    An LLM request can be valid JSON and still be the wrong request. The model may receive an old
    system instruction, duplicated history, stringified tool arguments or a truncated document. The
    reliable way to debug it is to inspect the final serialized payload at the network boundary—not
    the prompt template you expected your application to build.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <strong>Short version:</strong> preserve the raw request, format a copy, verify fields from the
    outside in, then compare the payload with the code path that produced it. Treat formatting as a
    viewing aid, not as evidence that the request was correct.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Start with the request that crossed the boundary</h2>
  <p>
    Log the object immediately before the SDK or HTTP client sends it. Earlier objects may still be
    changed by middleware, prompt assemblers, message trimming or provider adapters. A useful trace
    includes the provider, model, endpoint, request body and a correlation ID. Avoid logging API keys
    or authorization headers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Copy that request into the <a href="/prompt/">LLM Request Inspector</a>. It separates system,
    user, assistant and tool messages while preserving their order. Keep the original raw entry next
    to the formatted view so you can return to exact escaping and field names.
  </p>

  <h2>Verify the outer request fields first</h2>
  <p>
    Before reading the conversation, confirm the provider-level settings. A request sent to the wrong
    model or with an unexpected response mode can make correct prompt text behave differently.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Model:</strong> is it the model configured for this environment?</li>
    <li><strong>Token limit:</strong> can the response fit, or is it being cut short?</li>
    <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> was a deterministic workflow given a high-randomness value?</li>
    <li><strong>Response format:</strong> does the app expect text, JSON or tool use?</li>
    <li><strong>Tools:</strong> are names, descriptions and required fields present?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Read messages in the order the model received them</h2>
  <p>
    Message order is part of the input. Do not group all user messages together for convenience.
    Walk the sequence from top to bottom and ask what information was available at each assistant
    turn. Look for duplicated context, stale summaries and tool results attached after the message
    that was supposed to use them.
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`system: You may only answer from the supplied document.
user: Summarize the cancellation policy.
assistant: I do not have the document.
user: [document inserted here]`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    In this example the document exists in the payload, but it arrives after the assistant response.
    Formatting exposes the sequencing error immediately.
  </p>

  <h2>Inspect system and developer instructions for conflicts</h2>
  <p>
    Long system prompts often accumulate instructions from several layers. Search for repeated
    requirements about output format, language, tool use and refusal behavior. If two instructions
    conflict, identify which layer injected each one instead of adding a third instruction to cancel
    the previous two.
  </p>
  <p>
    Also check templated values. An empty placeholder such as <code>{`{{customer_policy}}`}</code> may
    leave a grammatical sentence that looks plausible while silently removing the only source the
    model was meant to use.
  </p>

  <h2>Decode tool calls as structured data</h2>
  <p>
    Tool arguments are a common source of double serialization. The application may expect an object
    but receive a JSON string containing another JSON document. Pretty-print the arguments and inspect
    their actual type before changing a schema.
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`// Expected
{"account_id":"acct_42","include_archived":false}

// Accidentally sent as a string
"{\"account_id\":\"acct_42\",\"include_archived\":false}"`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    Use the <a href="/json/">JSON Formatter &amp; Validator</a> for a nested block that will not
    parse. A line-and-column error usually points near the failure, but the real mistake may be an
    unescaped quote or missing comma immediately before it.
  </p>

  <h2>Check escaping only after structure</h2>
  <p>
    Literal <code>\n</code> can mean either an escaped line break in a serialized string or the two
    characters the model actually received. Determine which serialization layer you copied from
    before replacing it. Repeatedly unescaping a value can corrupt examples that intentionally teach
    escape sequences.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the log is clearly a string representation, the <a href="/unescape-prompt/">Unescape Prompt</a>
    tool can restore readable whitespace. Compare the result with the raw value before using it in a
    reproduction.
  </p>

  <h2>Build the smallest faithful reproduction</h2>
  <p>
    Once you find a suspicious section, remove unrelated history while preserving the provider,
    model, system instruction, failing message and relevant tool schema. A useful reproduction is not
    merely short; it retains the condition that causes the failure. Change one variable at a time and
    record which payload produced each result.
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>Save the original request and response under one correlation ID.</li>
    <li>Redact secrets and customer data without changing message structure.</li>
    <li>Remove unrelated turns and run the request again.</li>
    <li>Change the suspected field only.</li>
    <li>Compare the two payloads with the <a href="/diff/">Text Diff Checker</a>.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Use a repeatable request checklist</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>The logged payload is captured at the send boundary.</li>
    <li>The provider, model and response mode match the intended environment.</li>
    <li>System and developer instructions contain no stale or conflicting text.</li>
    <li>Messages and tool results appear in chronological order.</li>
    <li>Tool argument types match the application contract.</li>
    <li>Escaped content has been decoded exactly once.</li>
    <li>The reproduction contains no credentials or personal data.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Start with the <a href="/prompt/">LLM Request Inspector</a> when the payload is difficult to read,
    then move to JSON validation and diffing only for the blocks that need closer inspection. This
    keeps the debugging trail faithful to what the model actually received.
  </p>
</PageLayout>
